{"body":"## Context

#372 (MCP server) added `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` as a dependency and `serve.ts` imports it eagerly at the top of `bin/cli.ts` (line 53). This means **every** `npx sequant` command (`run`, `doctor`, `init`, etc.) loads the MCP SDK — even when the user has no intention of using MCP.

When the SDK isn't installed (or fails to resolve), this produces:
- 14 TypeScript build errors on main
- 5 test failures on main
- Every feature branch that rebases/merges from main inherits the breakage
- QA constantly has to distinguish "pre-existing on main" vs "introduced by this PR"

This caused friction during #369 (Aider) QA and merge.

## Problem Files

| File | Import Type | Impact |
|------|------------|--------|
| `bin/cli.ts:53` | `import { serveCommand } from "../src/commands/serve.js"` | Eager — breaks all CLI commands |
| `src/commands/serve.ts:10-11` | `import { StdioServerTransport, SSEServerTransport }` | Static — fails at import time |
| `src/mcp/server.ts:9` | `import { McpServer }` | Static — fails at import time |
| `src/mcp/tools/*.ts` | `import type { McpServer }` | Type-only — OK at runtime, fails tsc |
| `src/commands/doctor.ts:497` | `await import("../mcp/server.js")` | Dynamic — already handles failure correctly |

## Goal

Make the MCP SDK a truly optional dependency. `npx sequant run` and all non-MCP commands should work without the SDK installed.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `bin/cli.ts` lazy-loads `serve.ts` via dynamic `import()` inside the `.action()` handler
- [ ] `npx sequant run`, `npx sequant doctor`, `npx sequant init` work without `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` installed
- [ ] `npx sequant serve` gives a clear error if SDK is not installed (not a cryptic import failure)
- [ ] `npm run build` passes without the SDK installed (type-only imports need conditional handling)
- [ ] Tests pass without the SDK installed (MCP tests can be skipped with a guard)
- [ ] `doctor` MCP health check continues to work (already uses dynamic import — verify)

## Design

### CLI entry point (bin/cli.ts)

```typescript
// Before (eager):
import { serveCommand } from "../src/commands/serve.js";
program.command("serve").action(serveCommand);

// After (lazy):
program.command("serve").action(async (...args) => {
  try {
    const { serveCommand } = await import("../src/commands/serve.js");
    return serveCommand(...args);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("MCP server requires @modelcontextprotocol/sdk. Install: npm install @modelcontextprotocol/sdk");
    process.exit(1);
  }
});
```

### Type-only imports

`import type` is erased at runtime but fails `tsc`. Options:
1. Move MCP types to a local `.d.ts` file that mirrors the SDK types
2. Use `// @ts-ignore` with a comment (not ideal)
3. Make SDK a `peerDependency` with `"optional": true`

Option 3 is cleanest.

## Testing

- Remove `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` from `node_modules`, verify all non-MCP commands work
- Verify `npx sequant serve` gives a clear error
- Verify `npm run build` passes","comments":[],"labels":[{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACT-M2Rw","name":"bug","description":"Something isn't working","color":"d73a4a"},{"id":"LA_kwDOQzPeLM8AAAACcQdjCg","name":"multi-agent","description":"Multi-agent backend support and agent-agnostic architecture","color":"7B68EE"}],"state":"OPEN","title":"fix: lazy-load MCP SDK to prevent build failures when SDK is not installed"}

